  "summary": "Hercule Poirot arranges for Maud Williams to work as a housekeeper to assist James Bently. During a phone call, Maud expresses her willingness to quit her current job and take on the role, despite the potential for dealing with difficult people. Poirot then calls Mrs. Wetherby to recommend Maud for a trial period as a maid. Mrs. Wetherby, who is frustrated by the perceived ingratitude of foreign workers, accepts the offer, though she privately discusses the arrangement with someone in her house, noting that her husband, Roger, has an odd temper.\n\nAfter leaving Mollie Samsa’s house, Poirot meets Maud at the Blue Cat café in Gilchester. He warns her that a murderer is loose in the village, but Maud remains confident in her ability to handle herself. During their conversation, Maud reveals she has previously visited Broadchurch for business, where she visited Mrs. Samuels at the Long Grass Hotel. She also admits to seeing James Bently in Broadchurch shortly before the murder of Mrs. MacKenzie, noting that she had sent him a postcard to arrange a meeting. Additionally, Maud mentions seeing Robin Upward in Broadchurch, whom she approached for an autograph. She also notes her familiarity with the Cartwrights, mentioning that Mr. Cartwright is a potential future MP.",
